cuban president fidel castro is encouraging 
foreign investors to develop resort hotels in hopes of offsetting 
an economic crisis with tourist spending the mexican government 
news agency reported sunday 
castro kicked off a new beach resort construction program at the 
inauguration of a hotel built by private spanish investors with 
support from the cuban government tourism developer cubanacan the 
notimex agency reported 
at the inauguration thursday castro said cuba plans to spend 
10000 to develop hundreds of beach sites notimex reported 
the government is offering 10 years tax exemption to private 
tourism business developers notimex quoted cubanacan director 
abraham maciques as saying 
the newly inaugurated sol palmeras hotel is the first of eight 
hotels to be built with private foreign investment and government 
money in the cities of varadero santiago de cuba and havana the 
news agency said 
spanish finnish and soviet investors are working with cubanacan 
to build the hotels notimex reported 
it said 2000 new hotel rooms are expected to be ready by the 
end of 1990 and most of them will be in fourstar hotels 
the sol palmeras is part of a development in varadero 60 miles 
from havana notimex reported the hotel has 400 rooms and 32 
luxury suites 
the varadero tourist center is expected to generate 900 million 
a year the news agency reported 
