<TEXT>
a strong earthquake struck 
northern new zealand on sunday toppling a twostory building and 
cracking concrete beams in a shopping mall but causing no injuries 
officials said 
the quake in the town of dannevirke which measured 67 on the 
richter scale was the strongest to hit new zealand in 22 years 
according to the governments department of scientific and 
industrial research 
the temblor which also smashed windows in several buildings 
was felt throughout the region and as far away as the capital 
wellington 
sue emery editor of the dannevirke evening news said police 
had blocked off the towns main street to clean up the debris from 
a twostory building that collapsed and to clear up broken glass 
there was no power in the town for an hour after the temblor 
the quake felt horrendous ms emery said its pretty 
chaotic here people are going in all directions 
marion leiba a spokeswoman for the australian seismological 
center in canberra said the epicenter of the quake appeared to be 
offshore roughly 65 miles southeast of the north island town of 
napier 
dannevirke police spokesman les trigg confirmed that one 
building had collapsed and said a shopping mall had been sealed off 
after large concrete beams cracked exposing the steel reinforcing 
the richter scale is a guage of the energy released by an 
earthquake as measured by the ground motion recorded on a 
seismograph a quake measuring 6 on the scale can cause severe 
damage 
</TEXT>
