<DOCNO> AP900513-0014 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
both harvey gantt and andrew young are black 
democrats seeking statewide office but one wants a runoff election 
and the other doesnt highlighting one of the most sensitive 
divisions in southern politics 
some analysts call the runoff system racist others say it 
simply assures that a party runs its strongest nominee they agree 
however that minority and liberal candidates almost always lose 
when forced into oneonone runoffs with more conservative whites 
runoff elections are required in nine southern and border states 
if no primary candidate wins more than 50 percent of the vote on 
the first goround in north carolina the secondplace finisher 
can demand a runoff if the top votegetter garners less than 40 
percent 
gantt the former mayor of charlotte got 38 percent of the vote 
in north carolinas us senate primary last week he pleaded with 
secondplace finisher michael easley who is white to forgo a june 
5 runoff 
but easley refused and is expected to pick up most of those who 
supported the other two losing white candidates in the democratic 
primary the eventual winner will take on conservative republican 
sen jesse helms in november 
in georgia young is leading the democratic gubernatorial field 
with about 30 percent of the vote but he is opposed to a lawsuit 
filed last week that seeks to abolish the states runoff system 
its heightening the tensions in the state said merle 
black a politics and government professor at emory university 
it makes it much harder for him to get the share of the white 
vote that he needs he certainly doesnt want the rules changed in 
the middle of the game 
georgias runoff system was instituted in 1964 and sponsors of 
the legislation clearly indicated its purpose was to dilute black 
political strength 
but most runoff systems originated early in the century when 
blacks did not vote the south had virtually no republican party 
and a democratic primary victory was tantamount to election 
runoffs were used to narrow the democratic field and unify the 
party 
many political scientists swear by the principle of majority 
rule and some believe the runoff system should be universal 
i dont think you want to get a party nominee who represents 
only onefifth of the party said larry sabato of the university 
of virginia i would personally favor a 40 percent or 45 percent 
cutoff and having a runoff for all states because the dangers 
always present that you could get a very unrepresentative nominee 
party strength is the reason most often used to justify runoffs 
but some say the oneonone contests merely prolong vicious party 
infighting and can severely wound the eventual nominee 
all the republican has to do is pick up on all the charges 
and just continue the fight said thad beyle a political science 
professor at the university of north carolina 
william schneider a political analyst with the american 
enterprise institute said the runoffs in many instances are merely 
a way for democrats to avoid nominating blacks 
theres plenty of contest now from republicans in general 
elections he said so what is the purpose of the runoff to 
strengthen the party not necessarily theres another unspoken 
purpose to keep from nominating blacks or it could be phrased 
weaker candidates 
schneider called the runoff system a terrible racist idea 
that forces black candidates to prove themselves twice 
other analysts say runoffs are not inherently racist although 
racism can color the results and they say changing the nominating 
structure is not the way to deal with that problem 
eliminating runoffs wont eliminate racism said earl black 
a political scientist at the university of south carolina 
you have to make people confront their biases through 
education through religion through civil rights demonstrations 
this is how you reach people said sabato 
merle black who is earl blacks brother said runoffs have 
produced many prominent figures who won runoffs after secondplace 
primary finishes among them a young georgia democrat named sam 
nunn now chairman of the senate armed services committee 
by contrast he and others say the absence of runoffs can have 
disappointing results for example 
ray blanton who won a crowded tennessee primary with barely a 
fifth of the vote he became governor in 1974 and later was 
indicted on a variety of corruption charges 
marshall coleman who won virginias gop gubernatorial 
nomination with 37 percent of the vote and narrowly lost the 1989 
general election to douglas wilder 
the nine states that have runoffs if a primary candidate doesnt 
get 50 percent are alabama arkansas florida georgia louisiana 
oklahoma mississippi south carolina and texas 
