<TEXT>
democrats and republicans alike are 
reaffirming an old adage in their competing proposals for campaign 
finance reform if money is the mothers milk of politics lets 
dry up the other guys source 
with serious negotiations between leaders of the two parties in 
the senate scheduled to begin behind closed doors this week both 
are defining reform as weaning the other from its chief means 
of raising cash 
republicans describe as sewer money the estimated 45 
million to 60 million in unreported dollars that taxexempt 
organizations primarily unions spent last election on socalled 
independent getoutthevote drives largely on behalf of 
democratic candidates 
democrats accuse republicans of wanting to introduce more 
rather than less money into the political process by greatly 
expanding the role of wealthy individuals 
both want to increase the roles of their state and national 
party organizations as a conduit for money republicans with a 
much stronger party infrastructure already in place for raising and 
disbursing cash would do it much faster 
the two parties also agree on wanting to diminish the influence 
of political action committees or pacs an institution largely 
spawned by the last postwatergate round of reforms and 
republicans would like to abolish them entirely 
pacs accounted for 45 million or nearly onefourth of all the 
money spent on senate campaigns in 1988 nearly 80 percent of their 
contributions went to incumbents since there are more democratic 
than republican incumbents in congress democrats tend to benefit 
most from pac largesse 
president bush and republicans would prefer to eliminate pacs 
altogether but recognizing that the courts likely would hold such 
a broad ban to be an unconstitutional infringement on freedom of 
speech and association they have a fallback position 
union corporate and trade association pacs still would be 
abolished and the amounts that nonaffiliated ideological pacs 
such as those operated by the national rifle association 
environmental groups and both sides of the abortion issue can 
contribute to a candidate would drop from 10000 to 2000 per 
election cycle 
to make up for the lost revenue republicans would raise the 
25000 aggregate ceiling on individual contributions to candidates 
and parties for use in national elections to 340000 a year 
democrats contend the gop plan contains a loophole that would 
allow individuals to continue contributing even more money into 
state party coffers without having to report it to the federal 
election commission 
wealthy individuals and corporations could continue to give 
unlimited amounts of money to state party organizations senate 
democratic leader george mitchell of maine said of the republican 
proposal the practice that occurred in the 1988 elections when 
publicly funded presidential candidates raised upward of 45 
million in 100000 donations from individuals and corporations 
would continue unabated 
democrats would displace pacs with spending ceilings and a 
revived public financing scheme paid for by taxpayers 
volunteering to increase by 3 what they pay to the internal 
revenue service each year 
pacs would be prohibited by the democratic plan from 
contributing directly to candidates the limit on those 
contributions is now 10000 from any one pac to a candidate 
but the democrats would continue allowing pacs to give 15000 a 
year to party committees under their plan the national parties 
could still collect up to an aggregate 35 million a year from 
pacs and their senatorial campaign committees could collect another 
19 million 
the democrat bill fails the truthinadvertising test said 
senate republican leader bob dole of kansas what we have here in 
effect is a big moneylaundering scheme 
the rhetorical flourishes are expected to diminish once 
mitchell dole and four to five other key senators from the two 
sides begin negotiating behind closed doors later this week on 
seeking a compromise 
democrats are adamant that any compromise must contain some type 
of firm spending limits on candidates never declare republicans 
just as vehemently the average senatorial campaign in 1988 cost 
38 million 
both parties embraced portions of a bipartisan task forces 
recommendations calling for flexible ceilings but neither has 
accepted its suggestions entirely 
republicans rejected the task forces suggestion that a cap be 
placed on outofstate contributions instead adopting as a 
substitute the notion that nonresident donors should be limited to 
half or 500 what individuals can give directly to a candidate 
democrats likewise rejected the suggestion there should be no 
cap on small donations from instate contributors candidates could 
use those contributions to exceed the overall limits but only by 
25 percent under their proposal 
