president mikhail s gorbachev and president bush asking both to 
take our problem into their hearts 
landsbergis declined to release the text of what he called a 
diplomatic communication but said he and the presidents of 
neighboring latvia and estonia also had asked gorbachev to meet 
with them 
the baltic republics were forcibly annexed by the soviet union 
in 1940 they have taken advantage of gorbachevs reforms to wage a 
careful parliamentary push for sovereignty that suddenly took a 
sharp turn march 11 when lithuania defied moscow and declared its 
independence 
moscow imposed a partial economic embargo on lithuania and 
threatened the other two republics the sanctions have forced the 
layoff of 12000 people in lithuania according to official reports 
a tanker carrying 80000 tons of petroleum was en route sunday 
to the lithuanian port of klaipeda to relieve the gasoline shortage 
stemming from the blockade lithuanian television reported the oil 
was purchased with money from emigre lithuanians officials said 
it was not clear whether soviet authorities would allow the tanker 
to dock at klaipeda 
mrs prunskiene traveling as a private citizen met in 
washington with bush and with leaders in canada france britain 
and west germany 
although she was warmly received the west in general has 
adopted a cautious attitude toward the situation in lithuania 
unwilling to cause more trouble for gorbachev as he wrestles with 
domestic reform 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater emphasized that bushs 
may 3 meeting with mrs prunskiene did not change the us policy 
of not formally recognizing lithuania as a separate country 
mrs prunskiene said on sunday she was heartened that western 
leaders were pushing negotiations between lithuania and the 
kremlin the fact that they see us lithuania and the soviet 
union as partners in negotiations is a sign that were already 
seen as a state she said 
west german chancellor helmut kohl and president francois 
mitterrand of france proposed in an april 26 letter that lithuania 
temporarily suspend its independence and enter into talks with 
moscow 
the two sides are interpreting the kohlmitterrand letter 
differently but appear to be edging toward a compromise similar to 
what it proposes 
mrs prunskiene reiterated that lithuania was prepared to 
suspend new laws that concern moscow as a condition for talks and 
said she expected the kremlin to raise its economic blockade of the 
republic of 37 million 
