<TEXT>
poor productivity not meager budgets is the 
main problem of the nations schools a noted education researcher 
said sunday 
lewis j perelman of the hudson institute said american 
schools actually are shortchanging the nation by wasting some 100 
billion a year through sprawling bureaucracy and outmoded 
technology 
in a rebuttal to those who claim increased education spending 
will improve student achievement he said more spending on more 
of the same education will waste resources weaken the us economy 
and undermine the nations global competitiveness 
in a report released sunday the acanemia deception 
perelman said the united states spent 3310 to educate each 
student from preschool to grade 12 in 1985 the expenditure is 
second only to switzerland which spent 3683 the figures are 
based on a special 1985 index of purchasing power of industrial 
nations 
the statistics contradict a recent analysis by the economic 
policy institute that said the united states trailed 13 other 
industrial nations in spending on elementary and secondary 
education 
the epi recommended adding at least 20 billion per year to the 
nations kindergarten through 12th grade spending 
perelman a senior research fellow at the conservative hudson 
institute research group in indianapolis said the epi used 
tortured statistics in an attempt to discredit president bushs 
contention that the focus of education reform must no longer be on 
resources it must be on results 
perelman said better academic results do not require spending 
more on education and spending more on education is at least as 
likely to cause economic decline as to reverse it 
he said the united states spent 41 percent of its gross 
domestic product on kindergarten through 12th grades yet showed 
dismal achievement in mathematics and science 
south korea spent 31 percent on education spain 26 percent 
and the united kingdom 45 percent and all outperformed us 
students 
restructuring education does not require bigger budgets but 
different budget priorities he said 
key findings of perelmans report were 
us education labor costs were 93 percent of output compared 
with 54 percent for the average us business and 46 percent for 
hightech business 
education invests 100 to 1000 times less in research and 
development or in acquiring technology than most businesses and 
several thousand times less than hightechnology industries 
computers have been documented to increase efficiency and 
accelerate learning the report said there are 2 million computers 
in the nations 100000 schools about one for every 20 students 
that compares with 40 million personal computers in homes or one 
for every two homes 
among his recommendations perelman said 
every education and training institution organization and 
program in the united states should set aside at least 1 percent of 
its gross revenues for investment in research and development the 
funds could be pooled in a common fund administered by a new 
national institute for learning technology 
the goal of the new investment in educational initiative should 
be to double the productivity of us 
every student in america should have access to a distance 
learning network by the year 2001 he explained that teachers can 
instruct a variety of students across the state or country at the 
same time with the twoway video 
